Title: "Stan By Me"

Logline: An isolated weekend getaway for a social media influencer and her friends takes a sinister turn when her obsessive fans, infected by a mind-altering virus, begin to surround their vacation home.

Setting: A secluded cabin in a rural, wooded area

Treatment:

I. Introduction (Act 1)

KATE, a successful social media influencer, sets off for a weekend retreat with her two friends, JAMES and LUCY, who help manage her brand.
The trio arrives at the secluded cabin in their car, looking forward to a relaxing weekend and brainstorming content ideas.
To capture the picturesque environment, Kate posts a photo of the cabin on social media, inadvertently revealing their location.
The post catches the attention of her fans, or "stans," who begin making their way to the cabin.
II. Rising Action (Act 2)

As the group settles in, they notice the first stan, OLIVIA, wandering nearby, exhibiting subtle signs of psychosis.
The trio is initially confused but brushes it off as a coincidence, unaware of the incoming danger.
More stans arrive, their behavior becoming increasingly erratic and disturbing, displaying delusions, hallucinations, and paranoia.
It becomes apparent that the stans are infected by a mysterious mind-altering virus, causing their obsession with Kate to spiral out of control.
Trapped inside the cabin, Kate, James, and Lucy grow increasingly anxious as they observe the stans lurking around the property, peering in through windows and trying doors.

It‚Äôs hard to stand out when you have a lot of competition
But what if your business has a lot of competition?

Examples:
‚Ä¢ Flower Delivery
‚Ä¢ Cabinet Making
‚Ä¢ Plumbing
‚Ä¢ Painting
‚Ä¢ Storage

The list goes on.

For all these businesses, customers compare their options, struggle to quickly tell the difference, and choose one at random. It‚Äôs a gamble if you get the sale.

So let‚Äôs talk about how you stand out, when you have a lot of competitors.

Here‚Äôs your first steps to stand out
3 steps to make your business stand out:
1) Group customers by their needs
2) Break those needs down to actionable parts
3) Translate the parts to what you‚Äôll do for them
This way, you‚Äôll be focused on customers that your competitors aren‚Äôt, or provide value to those customers in a different way.

Let‚Äôs use a real business as an example as I walk you through each step. My friend, Barrett O‚ÄôNeill‚Äôs storage business, OnDemand Storage (ODS):
1) Identify customer
First, talk to your most loyal customers to see what needs they have in common.

These needs will give you an idea of what you do better than anyone else.

Steal these questions to get to know their needs:

‚ÄúWhen using [our solution], what are you ultimately trying to get done or accomplish?‚Äù

‚ÄúAre you using multiple solutions?‚Äù

‚ÄúWhat are you trying to accomplish as you pull together multiple products and services?‚Äù

‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the final output you‚Äôre looking for?‚Äù

Source: Questions came from this Jobs to be Done website.

From the interviews you‚Äôll create a list of outcomes that your customers are using your solution to achieve.

Phrase the outcomes as ‚ÄúI want to [do a task] so I can [achieve expected outcome]‚Äù

For a ‚Äútask‚Äù include both the action the customer wants to do, and the object the customer wants to do it to.

For example:
I want to store my business equipment during the summer so I can re-open my business in the fall.

2) Understand what the customer values
Now, we want to translate these needs into something your business can act on. You want to know what your customer values and how you can solve it better than anyone.

But the word ‚Äúvalue‚Äù is so vague.

Bain Consulting thought the word ‚Äúvalue‚Äù was too fluffy too. So they ran a study to break value down into it‚Äôs core elements. They found 30 ‚ÄúElements of Value.‚Äù

These elements are much more concrete.

Here‚Äôs why I‚Äôm so excited about this. If your customer says they want convenience what they really mean is these 4 elements:
‚Ä¢ Simplifies
‚Ä¢ Save time
‚Ä¢ Avoid hassle
‚Ä¢ Reduce effort

Those 4 elements are much easier to act on! Let‚Äôs do that in the next step.

Use the pyramid below to see what ‚Äúvalue‚Äù really means to your customers (and check out this article if you want more of an explanation).
Bain‚Äôs Elements of Value

3) Find values where you can win / application
Now you take those elements and come up with ideas on how your business can solve them better than anyone.

Let‚Äôs take that convenience example:
‚Ä¢ Simplifies
‚Ä¢ Save time
‚Ä¢ Avoid hassle
‚Ä¢ Reduce effort

Here‚Äôs the first 3 elements as an example for OnDemand Storage (ODS):

Simplifies:
Storage is complex if the items need to be picked up from multiple locations. ODS built in-house logistic software to make the logistics simpler.

Save time:
ODS can save time during initial move-in and save time during the storage period itself. A few examples: using autopay, having the facilities ready when users arrive, movers ready on arrival.

Avoid hassle:
The big hassle for commercial storage is when they need a space too big for standard storage units, but getting their own warehouse would be too expensive.

Barrett gives businesses this mid-sized storage space so they don‚Äôt need their own warehouse. Businesses don‚Äôt need insurance, employees, or a logistics network.

You don‚Äôt need a new idea
You‚Äôll notice that taking care of what customers value isn‚Äôt a new idea. ODS isn‚Äôt the first business to handle logistics for you.

What makes you different is that you understand what your customers value and message it to them so it‚Äôs clear you‚Äôre taking care of their specific needs.

In a later issue we‚Äôll cover how you message your differentiation so that customers know what makes you different.

Originally, John defined redundant information as information that is conserved under a certain resampling process (essentially Gibbs sampling): given initial samples of variables¬†

\(X\_1, \ldots, X\_n\)

, you repeatedly pick one of the variables at random and resample it conditioned on the samples of all the other variables. The information that you still have about the original variable values after resampling many times must have been redundant, i.e. contained in at least two variables.
